          "children": [], 
          "subject": "<p>Yes and thank you\u00a0</p>"
        }
      ], 
      "subject": "<p>Does i \u00a0(for w^n when n is odd) always cancel out when we multiply two polynomials?<br /><br /></p>"
    }, 
    {
      "folders": [], 
      "updated": "2017-09-14T20:32:23Z", 
      "no_upvotes": 0, 
      "uid": "idfwkf5jgsm3gg", 
      "created": "2017-09-14T20:32:23Z", 
      "type": "followup", 
      "no_answer": 0, 
      "id": "j7kwvoaayyk57u", 
      "anon": "no", 
      "bucket_name": "Week 9/10 - 9/16", 
      "config": {}, 
      "bucket_order": 7, 
      "data": {
        "embed_links": null
      }, 
      "children": [
        {
          "folders": [], 
          "updated": "2017-09-15T01:44:53Z", 
          "uid": "i4nkipeofrkrz", 
          "created": "2017-09-15T01:44:53Z", 
          "type": "feedback", 
          "id": "j7l81jufz7c3dd", 
          "anon": "no", 
          "bucket_name": "Week 9/10 - 9/16", 
          "config": {}, 
          "bucket_order": 7, 
          "data": {
            "embed_links": null
          }, 
          "children": [], 
          "subject": "<p>n will be 4 as well.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>The idea is that you will choose a value of n such as n is greater or equal to the degree of the resultant multiplication and n is a power of 2.</p>"
        }, 
        {
          "folders": [], 
          "updated": "2017-09-15T06:51:06Z", 
          "uid": "idfwkf5jgsm3gg", 
          "created": "2017-09-15T06:51:06Z", 
          "type": "feedback", 
          "id": "j7lizcxwx3p25a", 
          "anon": "no", 
          "bucket_name": "Week 9/10 - 9/16", 
          "config": {}, 
          "bucket_order": 7, 
          "data": {
            "embed_links": null
          }, 
          "children": [], 
          "subject": "<p>But in that case,\u00a0FFT(a,\u03c9) = (2, 0, 2, 0) and\u00a0FFT(b,\u03c9) = (2, 0, 2, 0) and c = (4, 0, 4, 0)</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>So for computing FFT<sup>-1</sup>(c)\u00a0= n<sup>-1</sup>FFT(c,\u00a0\u03c9<sup>-1</sup>)</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>$$\\frac{1}{4}$$$$\\begin{bmatrix}1&amp; 1 &amp; 1 &amp;1 \\\\1&amp; -i&amp; -1&amp; i\\\\ 1&amp; -1&amp; 1&amp; -1\\\\ 1&amp; i&amp; -1&amp; i\\end{bmatrix}$$ X $$\\begin{bmatrix}4\\\\ 0\\\\ 4\\\\ 0\\end{bmatrix} $$ = (2, 0, 2, 0)</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Then the solution will be 2$$x^{3}$$ &#43; 2x, which is not correct.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Am I missing here something ?</p>\n<p></p>\n<p></p>"
        }, 
        {
          "folders": [], 
          "updated": "2017-09-15T14:45:10Z", 
          "uid": "i4nkipeofrkrz", 
          "created": "2017-09-15T14:45:10Z", 
          "type": "feedback", 
          "id": "j7lzx0kqapw3uc", 
          "anon": "no", 
          "bucket_name": "Week 9/10 - 9/16", 
          "config": {}, 
          "bucket_order": 7, 
          "data": {
            "embed_links": null
          }, 
          "children": [], 
          "subject": "<p>I think you are absolutely right. To select $$n$$ we need to add 1 to the degree of the resultant polynomial and then select n as the next power of two.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>In this case, the degree of the polynomial will be 4, so we need n to be greater than 5, so we will select 8.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>That should solve the problem.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>What do you think?</p>"
        }, 
        {
          "folders": [], 
          "updated": "2017-09-15T15:16:13Z", 
          "uid": "idfwkf5jgsm3gg", 
          "created": "2017-09-15T15:16:13Z", 
          "type": "feedback", 
          "id": "j7m10xguvta6h4", 
          "anon": "no", 
          "bucket_name": "Week 9/10 - 9/16", 
          "config": {}, 
          "bucket_order": 7, 
          "data": {
            "embed_links": null
          }, 
          "children": [], 
          "subject": "<p>Yes I think you are right. But if we select n=8 then the computation starts becoming tricky as in this case,</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>$$w^{k}$$ = $$e^{\\frac{i2\u03c0k}{n}}$$ and n = 8</p>\n<p>$$w^{0}$$ = 1</p>\n<p>$$w^{1}$$ =\u00a0$$e^{\\frac{i2\u03c0}{8}}$$ = cos$$\\frac{\u03c0}{4}$$ &#43; i.sin$$\\frac{\u03c0}{4}$$ =\u00a0$$\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2}}$$ &#43; $$\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2}}$$ i</p>\n<p>$$w^{2}$$ = i</p>\n<p>and so on..</p>\n<p>Don&#39;t you think, this computation will not be as simple as it was for n=4?</p>\n<p></p>"
        }, 
        {
          "folders": [], 
          "updated": "2017-09-15T15:25:42Z", 
          "uid": "i4nkipeofrkrz", 
          "created": "2017-09-15T15:25:42Z", 
          "type": "feedback", 
          "id": "j7m1d50i36c7b1", 
          "anon": "no", 
          "bucket_name": "Week 9/10 - 9/16", 
          "config": {}, 
          "bucket_order": 7, 
          "data": {
            "embed_links": null
          }, 
          "children": [], 
          "subject": "<p>The professor already confirmed that they are not going to ask us to run FFT manually. For anything that&#39;s greater than n = 4, it will be really tricky to do it manually.</p>"
        }, 
        {
          "folders": [], 
          "updated": "2017-09-15T15:33:51Z", 
          "uid": "idfwkf5jgsm3gg", 
          "created": "2017-09-15T15:33:51Z", 
          "type": "feedback", 
          "id": "j7m1nlxh5ht7en", 
          "anon": "no", 
          "bucket_name": "Week 9/10 - 9/16", 
          "config": {}, 
          "bucket_order": 7, 
          "data": {
            "embed_links": null
          }, 
          "children": [], 
          "subject": "<p>Ok. One\u00a0last question. I just saw that in post &#64;277, professor mentioned that when the degree of polynomial is d, then we determine d &#43; 1 points. So do you think for polynomial of degree 4, n will be 5 instead of 8 ?</p>\n<p></p>"
        }, 
        {
          "folders": [], 
          "updated": "2017-09-15T15:43:46Z", 
          "uid": "i4nkipeofrkrz", 
          "created": "2017-09-15T15:43:46Z", 
          "type": "feedback", 
          "id": "j7m20d724445s2", 
          "anon": "no", 
          "bucket_name": "Week 9/10 - 9/16", 
          "config": {}, 
          "bucket_order": 7, 
          "data": {
            "embed_links": null
          }, 
          "children": [], 
          "subject": "<p>I think that&#39;s exactly what I was missing above. d &#43; 1 is the degree we should consider to compute $$n$$, but n should always be a power of 2. It won&#39;t work if it isn&#39;t.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>So, in your example, we need to consider d &#43; 1 = 5, so we need to use $$n = 8$$.</p>\n<p></p>"
        }, 
        {
          "folders": [], 
          "updated": "2017-09-15T17:22:31Z", 
          "uid": "idfwkf5jgsm3gg", 
          "created": "2017-09-15T17:22:31Z", 
          "type": "feedback", 
          "id": "j7m5jd8cqjk4qm", 
          "anon": "no", 
          "bucket_name": "Week 9/10 - 9/16", 
          "config": {}, 
          "bucket_order": 7, 
          "data": {
            "embed_links": null
          }, 
          "children": [], 
          "subject": "<p>Ok great. This answers my doubt. Thank you so much Santiago for your help.</p>"
        }
      ], 
      "subject": "<p>Thank you for the post Santiago.</p>\n<p>I got stuck in choosing value of n while solving similar problems. How do we choose value of n?</p>\n<p>For example, if we have two polynomials A(x) =\u00a0x\u00b2 &#43; 1 and B(x) =\u00a0x\u00b2 &#43; 1, then as per the logic mentioned above, the output polynomial will be of degree 4. In this case, what will be the value of n?</p>\n<p></p>"
    }, 
